<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Interlacing" class="currentChild" href="Interlacing">Interlacing</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
A scanning technique used in <a title="Cathode-Ray Tube" href="Cathode-Ray_Tube">cathode-ray tube</a>s in which the <a title="Electron Gun" href="Electron_Gun">electron gun</a> scans a line with each vertical passage as well as with each horizontal passage. Or, essentially, the gun constructs an image with two separate <a title="Field" href="Field">field</a>s. Usually, the gun draws first the even-numbered lines, then draws the odd-numbered lines, each set of lines being considered a field. Interlacing is used on television sets, but rarely on computer monitors with a <a title="Resolution" href="Resolution">resolution</a> less than 1024 x 768 <a title="Pixel" href="Pixel">pixel</a>s. Screens that are <a title="Interlaced" href="Interlaced">interlaced</a> tend to produce a flicker (called <a title="Interlace Flicker" href="Interlace_Flicker">interlace flicker</a>) whereas a <a title="Non-Interlaced" href="Non-Interlaced">non-interlaced</a> screens tend to have a more settled image. Also known as <a title="Interlaced Scanning" href="Interlaced_Scanning">interlaced scanning</a>. 
</p>
